    <body>
      <trans-unit id="11332" identifier="29587245fea6177d2282f2ca4a93001c">
        <source>{panel type=&quot;ct-algorithm&quot; title=&quot;Algorithmic thinking&quot;}</source>
        <target>crwdns11332:0crwdne11332:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11333" identifier="653892f84386e0674d6cad333b217aa4">
        <source>The steps we follow to calculate the barcode checksum is an Algorithm.</source>
        <target>crwdns11333:0crwdne11333:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[2]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11334" identifier="fdefb1dfcf170bb0cf43c92a5c1b477b">
        <source>We follow this same Algorithm every time we want to create a checksum for a
barcode, and every time we want to check if there is an error in a barcode.</source>
        <target>crwdns11334:0crwdne11334:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[2]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11335" identifier="cffb08d31bf521549d25ac2376b7f1a6">
        <source>It specifies exactly how we should do this, and students practice algorithmic
thinking as they follow and articulate this algorithm.</source>
        <target>crwdns11335:0crwdne11335:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[2]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11336" identifier="d4789df7fc6fae273d42b3ff89b932ef">
        <source>Examples of what you could look for:</source>
        <target>crwdns11336:0crwdne11336:0</target>
        <note>Context: Headline 4&#13;
XPath: /h4</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11337" identifier="3e8fdcf5416b1baf8ffe1d5bc3f46cfb">
        <source>Can your students write instructions that allow someone else to calculate the
barcode checksum of different products with the same number of digits in their
barcodes (e.g. 12)?</source>
        <target>crwdns11337:0crwdne11337:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[3]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11338" identifier="20c814ce4d99465329101ed6aeb3b40d">
        <source>What about instructions that can be used for any different product, regardless
of the number of digits?</source>
        <target>crwdns11338:0crwdne11338:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[3]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11339" identifier="1be4c01d2096b1876d7bd199ccb4c3b9">
        <source>{panel end}</source>
        <target>crwdns11339:0{panel end}crwdne11339:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[4]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11340" identifier="59ced97ef8757b49683caaf57e6207bd">
        <source>{panel type=&quot;ct-abstraction&quot; title=&quot;Abstraction&quot;}</source>
        <target>crwdns11340:0crwdne11340:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[5]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11341" identifier="492a81655ee021af79d86da21c4e859b">
        <source>When a barcode goes through a scanner the scanner reads the black and white
bars on the barcode, whereas when a human looks at a barcode they will read
the digits.</source>
        <target>crwdns11341:0crwdne11341:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[6]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11342" identifier="f12c803b901b4b41f2ba3c2eb447d4bf">
        <source>The numbers on the barcode and the black and white bars both represent the
same thing though - a numeric code that identifies a product, and the bars
are an abstracted representation of these numbers.</source>
        <target>crwdns11342:0crwdne11342:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[6]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11343" identifier="2a9a0245d538cb88371b0639b6ed8e53">
        <source>When we are calculating the checksum we also don’t need to think about what
product it actually represents is, we just want to find out whether or not
the barcode is correct and all we need to do that is the barcode itself.</source>
        <target>crwdns11343:0crwdne11343:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[7]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11344" identifier="7ca1cce9bc789f9d38045770108363e7">
        <source>Examples of what you could look for:</source>
        <target>crwdns11344:0crwdne11344:0</target>
        <note>Context: Headline 4&#13;
XPath: /h4[2]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11345" identifier="4171075d0b66b529b86a8f597e8ecb4d">
        <source>Can your students explain how both of these represent the product?
Can they explain the reason for the different representations?</source>
        <target>crwdns11345:0crwdne11345:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[8]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11346" identifier="95e2aef312d8003ea83532ea9651f31f">
        <source>{panel end}</source>
        <target>crwdns11346:0{panel end}crwdne11346:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[9]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11347" identifier="16c5229b7bb0bd77299bb63485055923">
        <source>{panel type=&quot;ct-decomposition&quot; title=&quot;Decomposition&quot;}</source>
        <target>crwdns11347:0crwdne11347:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[10]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11348" identifier="1b14d3a5eb788980cf6f823940bfa07e">
        <source>To check the product code, the task of calculating the checksum is broken
down into individual steps: adding one number at a time; doing that for
each subset of digits.</source>
        <target>crwdns11348:0crwdne11348:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[11]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11349" identifier="9fcf49e2637fde9fe144c8665b3b1255">
        <source>By doing this we are decomposing the problem into smaller subtasks which are
easier to solve than the overall problem of “Is this barcode correct?”.</source>
        <target>crwdns11349:0crwdne11349:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[11]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11350" identifier="45822e9f68cc2ea0b9079a1838b37e9f">
        <source>Each time we solve one of these subtasks we move on to the next and move
closer to a solution.</source>
        <target>crwdns11350:0crwdne11350:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[11]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11351" identifier="833d815031c5d5819a2b19b8c4affd40">
        <source>Examples of what you could look for:</source>
        <target>crwdns11351:0crwdne11351:0</target>
        <note>Context: Headline 4&#13;
XPath: /h4[3]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11352" identifier="32559908ad675530b34e00a497dc9057">
        <source>Are students able to independently break the calculation into the two halves,
and then perform the additions on each group of values, and combine them
to get the checksum?</source>
        <target>crwdns11352:0crwdne11352:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[12]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11353" identifier="a1cbd26cbb10243bfd45ce5b5ea130b4">
        <source>Can they do this for a range of different codes with different errors in them?</source>
        <target>crwdns11353:0crwdne11353:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[12]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11354" identifier="b1c2847763ba990ce3b79c43c0f66f9e">
        <source>{panel end}</source>
        <target>crwdns11354:0{panel end}crwdne11354:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[13]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11355" identifier="40ad58809f56a2bf712e4dcd43bbd5e7">
        <source>{panel type=&quot;ct-pattern&quot; title=&quot;Generalising and patterns&quot;}</source>
        <target>crwdns11355:0crwdne11355:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[14]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11356" identifier="68f32ded76e3dd12f8c8d1db80c3edf3">
        <source>The same method can apply to shorter (e.g. 8-digit) and longer product codes.</source>
        <target>crwdns11356:0crwdne11356:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[15]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11357" identifier="2ed7a5df91d58028a3139e503bfcfb38">
        <source>If you look at some courier packages you might see much larger bar codes,
and these use similar error detection techniques.</source>
        <target>crwdns11357:0crwdne11357:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[15]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11358" identifier="9bddd12109f1230125e25a47b468e08b">
        <source>To check each of these bar codes we follow the same algorithmic pattern of
using the numbers on the code (except for the last one) and applying a
mathematical formula to these to get the final digit (or what it should be
if there are no errors!).</source>
        <target>crwdns11358:0crwdne11358:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[15]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11359" identifier="ec993088561d59b2638cc84170b056e3">
        <source>Examples of what you could look for:</source>
        <target>crwdns11359:0crwdne11359:0</target>
        <note>Context: Headline 4&#13;
XPath: /h4[4]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11360" identifier="b31613841c57e5b362ed32df62d9b7de">
        <source>Can students apply the algorithm (the version starting at the right hand end)
to different length product codes?</source>
        <target>crwdns11360:0crwdne11360:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[16]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11361" identifier="a5344f3ef2dd7035f2f68e49d7cf47eb">
        <source>Do they appreciate how it still checks the digits in each case?</source>
        <target>crwdns11361:0crwdne11361:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[16]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11362" identifier="86a85f2b4e7a661cfe1eb2d36b85fb07">
        <source>(You can find different codes by searching for images of barcodes online).</source>
        <target>crwdns11362:0crwdne11362:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[16]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11363" identifier="29865c6bd6223a870160b434de9c35ce">
        <source>{panel end}</source>
        <target>crwdns11363:0{panel end}crwdne11363:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[17]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11364" identifier="adab59f4c0dc0ca178defb9b221dd176">
        <source>{panel type=&quot;ct-evaluation&quot; title=&quot;Evaluation&quot;}</source>
        <target>crwdns11364:0crwdne11364:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[18]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11365" identifier="c76b354b431b2a93c40f7aab02c88617">
        <source>This error detecting process isn't perfect.</source>
        <target>crwdns11365:0crwdne11365:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[19]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11366" identifier="09ff38a7f36a13bf0cf1a9d7eb5f58ab">
        <source>To evaluate its effectiveness we need to thoroughly test it.</source>
        <target>crwdns11366:0crwdne11366:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[19]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11367" identifier="fe32e1001cfe682b7dc91b5f0a18f7f8">
        <source>Ask students what the different ways we need to test the algorithm are.</source>
        <target>crwdns11367:0crwdne11367:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[19]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11368" identifier="08b77569cd3517fb800a43561ebad686">
        <source>Interestingly it is not enough to just test it with a bunch of different
barcodes with one number in them changed, we need to test a range of
different types of errors as well!</source>
        <target>crwdns11368:0crwdne11368:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[19]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11369" identifier="238cd9c00c8014263847380845a56fe0">
        <source>For example what if instead of one number changing two of the numbers are
switched around?</source>
        <target>crwdns11369:0crwdne11369:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[19]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11370" identifier="963cf57ac311059c519ac76a58baae5d">
        <source>What if two numbers are changed?</source>
        <target>crwdns11370:0crwdne11370:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[19]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11371" identifier="1fa7afc4f8ec86fd52063eb2b942048b">
        <source>Are there any situations where we couldn’t figure out if something had changed?</source>
        <target>crwdns11371:0crwdne11371:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[19]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11372" identifier="dc7cfd90b202c216be0d0168c42220c3">
        <source>This is an example of an important technique used when evaluating algorithms
and programs, called edge case testing.</source>
        <target>crwdns11372:0crwdne11372:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[20]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11373" identifier="ee945efc504e5ccf8a3f1c6b2bc14938">
        <source>Examples of what you could look for:</source>
        <target>crwdns11373:0crwdne11373:0</target>
        <note>Context: Headline 4&#13;
XPath: /h4[5]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11374" identifier="858d27b971ccf45e9e4226ad627b9f9c">
        <source>Can students demonstrate what kind of errors the checksum is guaranteed
to detect?</source>
        <target>crwdns11374:0crwdne11374:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[21]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11375" identifier="61ba79ca9220803e29049cdcb2a5e011">
        <source>Can they give examples of errors that a human might make when typing in a
number that wouldn't be detected?</source>
        <target>crwdns11375:0crwdne11375:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[21]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11376" identifier="36b7811797b00e96075c0f04d2bc7540">
        <source>Can they work out how likely it is that an error will go undetected in each
of these cases?</source>
        <target>crwdns11376:0crwdne11376:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[21]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11377" identifier="3788ec149cd16ec0265b896195cd6a57">
        <source>They can do this by trial and error or by logical reasoning.</source>
        <target>crwdns11377:0crwdne11377:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[21]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11378" identifier="0d3de6c21e2d458b6944fce764817b3f">
        <source>{panel end}</source>
        <target>crwdns11378:0{panel end}crwdne11378:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[22]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11379" identifier="d167885c0977f1b6d43c86a3424970a4">
        <source>{panel type=&quot;ct-logic&quot; title=&quot;Logic&quot;}</source>
        <target>crwdns11379:0crwdne11379:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[23]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11380" identifier="77503b0a72c7c9addeddb02a8f9f8c84">
        <source>The algorithm is designed to be sensitive to the type of errors that are
most likely to happen.</source>
        <target>crwdns11380:0crwdne11380:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[24]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11381" identifier="1bc15b3379a0a74b42ff366fe111fbea">
        <source>We can also evaluate the algorithm using logical thinking.</source>
        <target>crwdns11381:0crwdne11381:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[25]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11382" identifier="d2663645150b5be5b55859ada486fd3c">
        <source>Examples of what you could look for:</source>
        <target>crwdns11382:0crwdne11382:0</target>
        <note>Context: Headline 4&#13;
XPath: /h4[6]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11383" identifier="50089d271e8e0d9096cde958792a2f13">
        <source>Can students explain the logic that was applied in the process of
designing a barcode checksum, and especially the choice to multiply some
of the numbers by 3?</source>
        <target>crwdns11383:0crwdne11383:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[26]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11384" identifier="b5feca34bf0b61ebb2a6023917e19340">
        <source>In cases where the checksum is unable to detect and error can students
explain logically why the error cannot be detected?</source>
        <target>crwdns11384:0crwdne11384:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[27]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11385" identifier="d871d9839b19bd202423ecc559922cb0">
        <source>{panel end}</source>
        <target>crwdns11385:0{panel end}crwdne11385:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[28]</note>
      </trans-unit>
